Evolution of Message Diffusal Speed

US Presidential Election Debate 3

Aman Abhishek

July 10, 2018

For this analysis, I have extracted all “retweet chains” that had a length of more than 200. That is, the original tweet was retweeted at least 200 times within the timespan of the debate.

The retweet chain were ordered chronologically, and then the “speed” of retweets was calculated by using a N-retweet moving window, where speed is inverse (1/x) of time. For example:

let’s say a tweet got tweeteed at t=0, and retweeted at t=1,2,4,8

if we select the window length (N) to be 3, then

the the intial speed is 1/(2-0) = 0.5

for next stage the speed is 1/(4-1) = 0.7

and at the last stage its 1/(8-2) = 0.2

Therefore the speed evoloved as 0.5,0.7,0.2; and I would say that for “order” 1 speed is 0.5, for order 2 its 0.7 and for order 3 its 0.2.

For some other N, these values would be different. For this analysis, I have chosen N=114 for reasons I would skip here.

Below are some plots for the full dataset of debate 3. The color reflects how my followers the original tweeter has (note the log scale on color).

ggplot(data=df,mapping=aes(x=order,y=speed, group=cat))+
  geom_smooth(se=FALSE,mapping = aes(color=log((followers_count))))+
  labs(title="All retweet chains")
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam'

Note that the retweet chains that do not extend to higher orders (right side of the x-axis) reflect that they are relatively shorter. In other words, they did not get retweeted as much.

ggplot(data=filter(df,verified=="True"),mapping=aes(x=order,y=speed, group=cat))+
  geom_smooth(se=FALSE,mapping = aes(color=log((followers_count))))+
  labs(title="All retweet chains started by a verified account")
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam'

The general trend for the top two curves is how the speed increases rapidly, and then falls rapidly. This seems to suggest a mechanism of diffusal where the original tweeters themselves are powering the diffusion. The cases where there is a fall followed by a rise(s) might point to the tweet being retweeted by a user who is a central network node, which leads to an increase in the retweeting speed.

ggplot(data=filter(df,verified=="False"),mapping=aes(x=order,y=speed, group=cat))+
  geom_smooth(se=FALSE,mapping = aes(color=log((followers_count))))+
  labs(title="All retweet chains started by a non-verified account")
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam'

Below, I am removing the anamolous case (really steep peak) in the above figure to get a better look.

ggplot(data=filter(df,verified=="False" & cat != 253),mapping=aes(x=order,y=speed, group=cat))+
  geom_smooth(se=FALSE,mapping = aes(color=log((followers_count))))+
  labs(title="All retweet chains started by a non-verified account (2)")
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam'

More interesting curves. The curve which extends to order > 4000 is by a twitter user Oliverdirtyb who had 2397 followers at that time, and tweeted this. Oliverdirtyb is now verified - maybe because of this tweet?!

One can isolate curves of interest. For example, Oliverdirtyb’s tweet:

ggplot(data=filter(df, cat == 1063),mapping=aes(x=order,y=speed, group=cat))+
  geom_smooth(se=TRUE,color="blue")+
  geom_point(alpha=0.1,size=0.1)+
  labs(title="Slowly gone viral tweet by a not-so-elite user: Oliverdirtyb")
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam'
